\begin_layout Standard
For Coulomb potentials, the field of an infinite sheet of charge is uniform.
 Its strength does not vary with distance from the sheet, nor does its direction.
 This is normally derived by making use of Gauss' law.
 Indeed, it may be shown that, in three dimensions, any force that obeys
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

 potential satisfies Gauss' law XXX and vice versa XXX.
 Our experiment is a test of the uniformity of the gravitational field of
 an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sheet of mass.
 It is in this sense that our experiment is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Gauss' law test of gravity.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In its idealized form, our experiment compares the gravitational field strength
 at two distances from an infinite sheet of mass.
 Finite sheet masses are suspended on opposite sides of a torsion pendulum
 aligned parallel to their moment arms, but displaced in opposite directions
 perpendicular to the arms.
 If there is an inverse square law violating force between the sheets on
 the pendulum and an infinite sheet of matter, the pendulum will feel a
 torque.
 If the distance between the pendulum and the sheet is modulated, the torque
 will vary in sync with the modulation.
 If there are no inverse square law violating interactions between the pendulum
 and sheet, the pendulum will experience 
\emph on
no torque
\emph default
.
 The difficulties in the measurement primarily involve ensuring that the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite sheet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation is valid and that gravity is the only messenger between the
 infinite sheet and the pendulum.
 
\end_layout

