\begin_layout Standard
Three dimensional plots are difficult to read, three dimensional plots with
 errorbars are worse.
 Furthermore, the scatter in a plot like Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "TriangleScatterPlot"

\end_inset

 is dominated by the noisiest points.
 As shown in XXX (plot of noise vs.
 time), the noise in PlateWash varies by orders of magnitude with environmental
 conditions; we're interested mostly in the points with least scatter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to present the result in a meaningful and two-dimensional way,
 the 'triangle plot' was developed.
 In order to improve the statistics by a factor of two, we make the assumption
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau(a,b)=\Delta\tau(b,a)$
\end_inset

, and fold the points over the 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

 axis.
 In order to plot points with uncertainties, measurements are plotted as
 circles in the 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

 is represented by the radius of the circle.
 To provide an errorbar, the region from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau+\sigma_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau-\sigma_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is plotted in grey.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau-\sigma_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Delta\tau+\sigma_{\tau}|$
\end_inset

 are greater than zero (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 a point is off-zero with 1-
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 significance), the remainder of the circle is filled in with color.
 To represent the sign of the datapoint, yellow is negative, and blue is
 positive XXX (check sign).
 Any force of nature should satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau(a,a)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Any conservative force should be associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau(a,c)=\Delta\tau(a,b)+\Delta\tau(b,c)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method has limitations.
 Large signals, or large uncertainties produce large circles, which can
 hide smaller, more significant, points.
 For sparsely sampled data, however, it can be very helpful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bootstrap
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis presented here makes extensive use of a statistical method
 called 'the bootstrap' or 'bootstrapping'.
 Its primary merit in this context is that it allows straightforward and
 reasonably robust estimation of confidence intervals.
 Its support rests upon the premise that the best estimator for the distribution
 from which a data set is drawn is the data set itself.
 The idea is to 'resample' the data to create synthetic data sets which
 may be passed through any analysis routine developed for the original data
 set.
 With repetition, this process generates distributions of important output
 quantities (best-fit points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-\lambda$
\end_inset

 space, for example) without recourse to complex error estimation/propagation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resampling scheme used in this analysis was to replace a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1/e$
\end_inset

 of the data points in a data set with others randomly selected from the
 initial data set.
 There is a related class of methods called 'the jackknife' that generate
 statistics by considering complete sets of subsets of data.
 
\end_layout

